  "texts": [
    "Recent studies by Aghajanyan et al. (2020) and Kopiczko et al.",
    "(2023) indicate that the upper bound for intrinsic dimensions is substantially smaller than what is typically used in such methods.",
    "For example, the d 90 value (the minimum number of trainable parameters required to reach 90% of the performance of the fully-parameter fine-tuned model) for the RoBERTa base is reported to be 896.",
    "However, when LoRA is applied to fine-tune this model, the number of trainable parameters escalates to 0.3 million, suggesting the potential for further reduction in parameter count.",
    "In addition to the issue of requiring too many adjustable parameters, existing PEFT methods (Mao et al., 2021; He et al., 2021; Ding et al., 2022) primarily focus on the design of lightweight modules and their integration (or placement) within base models."
  ],
